# Exploration 003 Summary

## Goal

Define quantitative delayed-transfer metrics for the
`exact-ns-phase-locking-firewall`
branch from the already-frozen intrinsic object and search class, then issue a
clean verdict on whether Chain Step 2 is now well-posed.

## What I Tried

- Read the active chain, planning-run attack/judgment record, mission context,
  and controller memo to recover the exact Step-1 metric obligations.
- Read Exploration 001 and Exploration 002 to import the already-frozen
  intrinsic object
  `Mu_S(a)`
  and the exact closed-support search class.
- Reused the predecessor mission only for two bounded purposes:
  the local robustness precedent that rejects single-trajectory luck, and the
  fact that leakage control is required but its precise functional is still a
  branch-level policy choice.
- Converted those inputs into one support-level metric sheet using exact energy
  balances, cumulative turnover units, a strict viscous deadline, one numeric
  spectator-burden threshold, and one explicit robustness bar.

## Outcome

`succeeded`

## One Key Takeaway

Chain Step 2 can start: the branch now has a quantitative metric sheet sharp
enough to kill weak later successes. Delayed transfer means
`1/16` pre-event dormancy up to two support turnovers, then a first event with
simultaneous source loss and target gain each at least `1/4` of initial source
energy after at least three support turnovers but before `tau_nu / 4`, with
spectator burden capped by `B_spec <= 1/4` and success required on an open
parameter regime rather than one tuned orbit.

## Leads Worth Pursuing

- Step 2 should enumerate the frozen smallest-first ladder of finite helical
  supports and record enough exact ledger data to build
  `Q_S`,
  `N_turn`,
  and the later spectator burden.
- Step 3 should predeclare one fixed `A / B / R` partition on each survivor
  before any trajectory scoring and then derive the exact phase-amplitude
  ledger on that frozen partition.
- Step 4 should test the delayed-transfer metric only on supports that survive
  recursive closure and at least one admissible enlargement audit.

## Unexpected Findings

- The strongest metric improvement came from switching from a one-time turnover
  proxy to cumulative turnover count
  `N_turn(t)`;
  the local record demanded "intrinsic clocks," and the cumulative clock is
  materially harder to game.
- The predecessor mission's repaired packet leakage sheet could not be imported
  directly; its class labels are honest on that packet ledger but non-intrinsic
  for the present closed-support branch.

## Computations Worth Doing Later

- For each surviving Step-2 support, compute the exact triad list and the
  coefficient-weighted activity
  `Q_S(t)`.
- On any Step-3 candidate regime, evaluate
  `J_A`,
  `J_B`,
  `J_R`,
  `N_turn`,
  and
  `tau_nu`
  explicitly to see whether the frozen delayed-transfer event can ever occur.
- If a candidate appears promising, test whether the same fixed
  `A / B / R` partition works on an open parameter set rather than only on one
  tuned orbit.

